{"questionId":"3588796","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The scientist conducts a second experiment with a different species of bacteria.</p>\n<p>The population of this bacteria, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>S</mi></math> , can be modelled by the function</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>S</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>5000</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><msup><mn>65</mn><mi>t</mi></msup></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>0</mn></math>,</p>\n<p>where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math> is the number of hours since both experiments began.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math> when the two populations of bacteria are equal.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>equating <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>P</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>)</mo></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>S</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>)</mo></math> <strong>OR</strong> equating each function to a common variable&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong> (M1)</strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1200</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><msup><mn>5</mn><mi>t</mi></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>5000</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><msup><mn>65</mn><mi>t</mi></msup></math>;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1200</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><msup><mn>5</mn><mi>t</mi></msup><mo>=</mo><mi>x</mi></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5000</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><msup><mn>65</mn><mi>t</mi></msup><mo>=</mo><mi>x</mi></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>43</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>(</mo